acc <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/xdaiISU/ds202materials/master/hwlabs/fars2017/accident.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
acc1 <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/xdaiISU/ds202materials/master/hwlabs/fars2017/person.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

#1) Are there some days of the week where more accidents happen than the others (see FARS manual, use variable DAY_WEEK)?

ggplot(acc, aes(x = DAY_WEEK)) + geom_bar(fill = 'maroon') + scale_x_discrete(limit = c('Sunday', 'Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday')) + ggtitle('Number of Fatal Accidents Per Day of the Week') + xlab('Day of the Week') + ylab('Count')

#Explanation: From looking at the graph above, it’s apparent that the end of the week has more accidents. Saturday has the most fatal accidents, with a count close to 6,000. During the middle of the week, accidents stay pretty consistent around 4,000, but as the weekend nears, they go up steadily. This pattern makes sense because most of these accidents could be tied to drunk driving, where the weekend is typically when people are more likely to drink, go to the bars, and/or have parties.

#6) Tally the number of accidents by day of the week (DAY_WEEK), hour of the day (HOUR) and gender (SEX). Visualize the results and explain what you find.

joinedtables$HOUR <- as.integer(joinedtables$HOUR)
joinedtables2 <- joinedtables %>%
  filter(HOUR != "99" & SEX <=3) %>%
  mutate(Sex = if_else(SEX == 1, 'Male', 'Female')) %>%
  group_by(HOUR, DAY_WEEK, Sex) %>%
  summarize(ACCIDENTS = n()) %>%
  mutate(SEX = as.factor(Sex))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'HOUR', 'DAY_WEEK'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
joinedtables2$Weekday <- wday(joinedtables2$DAY_WEEK, label = T)

ggplot(joinedtables2, aes(x = HOUR, y = ACCIDENTS, color = SEX)) + geom_line() + facet_wrap(~DAY_WEEK)

#Explanation: From the graphs we can observe that males get into more accidents than females overall. However, both males and females follow a similar pattern of rises and declines in accidents throughout each week day. Males and females tend to get into the most accidents around midnight on Sunday (day 1) and the late afternoon-evening on every day of the week. Friday (day 6) and Saturday (day 7) see the highest peaks in accidents among the other days, and this peak is in the late evening. Saturday, as well as Sunday, also see high accident peaks just after midnight. The fact that Friday, Saturday and Sunday show the highest peaks in accidents makes sense because people are more likely to go out to drink on these days and drunk drive afterward.

It looks like the areas with the highest count of accidents are in the south, primarily counties in the southwest regions of California and Arizona, the southern midwest in the Texas area, and the southeastern area around Florida. These areas had counts of fatalities between 1200 and 1600, whereas several locations in the midwest and northern regions had counts between 400 and 800. The gray areas on the map depict regions where there were no accidents reported at all; these are mainly centered in the midwest, and are sparsely scattered in both the east and west sides of the United States.

#8) Is summer or winter more dangerous? Does this depend on states? Explore and explain.

joinedtables$MONTH <- as.integer(joinedtables$MONTH)
joinedtables3 <- joinedtables %>%
  filter(MONTH != c(3, 4, 5, 9, 10) & INJ_SEV >=4) %>%
  mutate(MONTH = ifelse(MONTH == c(6, 7, 8), 'Summer', 'Winter')) %>%
  group_by(MONTH, INJ_SEV) %>%
  summarize(ACCIDENTS = n()) %>%
  mutate(MONTH = as.factor(MONTH))
## Warning in MONTH != c(3, 4, 5, 9, 10): longer object length is not a multiple of
## shorter object length
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'MONTH'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(joinedtables3, aes(x = INJ_SEV, y = ACCIDENTS, color = MONTH)) + geom_line() + facet_wrap(~MONTH)

#Explanation: The time series plot above does a great job of showing the severity of car accidents in the summer months of June, July, and August, as well as the winter months of November, December, January, and February. It looks like winter is more dangerous in terms of the amount of accidents that are charecterized as being “fatal”, with INJ_SEV values between 4 and 9. Seeing as the winter months have a larger amount of fatal accidents, we could infer that states expierencing more fatalities would be areas with harsher winter weather conditions such as northern states like Minnesota, North/South Dakota, Wisconsin, Montana, etc.
